00:04:01.240 --> 00:04:04.770
"In the '80s, I had
a job as a waiter

00:04:04.770 --> 00:04:07.490
at a place in Jersey City
called the Summit House.

00:04:07.490 --> 00:04:10.320
And one of the first
tables I ever waited on

00:04:10.320 --> 00:04:15.290
was a deuce in restaurant lingo,
a middle aged married couple

00:04:15.290 --> 00:04:18.029
for whom Friday night dinner
at this particular spot

00:04:18.029 --> 00:04:22.340
was a custom, a ritual
they'd really spruce up for.

00:04:22.340 --> 00:04:26.950
He always in a carefully pressed
polo shirt, seersucker jacket,

00:04:26.950 --> 00:04:32.490
and dark slacks, she in some
sort of floral print dress,

00:04:32.490 --> 00:04:35.560
pretty earrings, a pretty
tortoise shell comb

00:04:35.560 --> 00:04:38.700
in her hair, that sort of thing.

00:04:38.700 --> 00:04:43.190
The husband pronounced
his Rs as Ws,

00:04:43.190 --> 00:04:46.950
a speech defect called
R-labialization,

00:04:46.950 --> 00:04:53.480
most famously portrayed,
of course, by Elmer Fudd.

00:04:53.480 --> 00:04:57.200
So this exceedingly pleasant,
exceedingly soft spoken guy

00:04:57.200 --> 00:05:00.140
would, each and
every Friday evening,

00:05:00.140 --> 00:05:06.750
invariably order a "Wob
Woy," very "dwy," a "wum"

00:05:06.750 --> 00:05:11.680
and Coke for my wife, the
"pwime" "wib" very "wawe,"

00:05:11.680 --> 00:05:16.170
and the "bwoiled scwod."
'And would it be possible

00:05:16.170 --> 00:05:20.010
for my wife to have
that with "wice"

00:05:20.010 --> 00:05:24.570
instead of "fwench fwies,"'
he'd politely ask each and every

00:05:24.570 --> 00:05:25.980
time.

00:05:25.980 --> 00:05:29.780
I never questioned the
authenticity of the order.

00:05:29.780 --> 00:05:33.210
Yes, it seemed
improbable that someone

00:05:33.210 --> 00:05:35.930
who couldn't
pronounce the letter R

00:05:35.930 --> 00:05:39.950
would never, just randomly in
the course of events, order

00:05:39.950 --> 00:05:45.320
anything R-less, say a
gin and tonic or a scotch

00:05:45.320 --> 00:05:48.410
or a steak or a veal chop
or spaghetti and meatballs

00:05:48.410 --> 00:05:50.550
or a chicken pot pie.

00:05:50.550 --> 00:05:52.550
But I just figured
he knew what he

00:05:52.550 --> 00:05:55.590
liked, knew what his wife
liked, and that was that.

00:05:55.590 --> 00:05:58.220
He seemed like a perfectly
decent sort of guy,

00:05:58.220 --> 00:06:02.360
and I had absolutely no
reason to doubt his sincerity.

00:06:02.360 --> 00:06:05.860
And there'd always be dessert,
the inevitable "bwead" putting

00:06:05.860 --> 00:06:09.200
and "wed" velvet
cake, and at least

00:06:09.200 --> 00:06:12.280
two "bwandies," all
of which added up

00:06:12.280 --> 00:06:14.870
to a hefty check for two
people with a potentially

00:06:14.870 --> 00:06:16.260
substantial tip.

00:06:16.260 --> 00:06:19.630
So you want to be as
accommodating as possible.

00:06:19.630 --> 00:06:24.690
One Friday night-- this must
have been after waiting on them

00:06:24.690 --> 00:06:28.000
for two or three weeks
in a row, the husband

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:31.217
asked me some variation on
the question, assuming you

00:06:31.217 --> 00:06:32.800
don't want to be a
professional waiter

00:06:32.800 --> 00:06:35.240
all your life, what do
you really want to do?

00:06:35.240 --> 00:06:39.970
And I said that I wanted
to be a writer someday.

00:06:39.970 --> 00:06:44.150
And he said that he and
his wife loved to read.

00:06:44.150 --> 00:06:46.740
And I asked who are
your favorite writers.

00:06:46.740 --> 00:06:49.080
And he thought for a
moment and he said,

00:06:49.080 --> 00:06:54.340
'I love Joseph "Conwad,"
"Waymond" Chandler,

00:06:54.340 --> 00:06:58.680
and especially "Gwaham Gweene."'

00:06:58.680 --> 00:07:04.190
Now at this point, I
remember I did look around,

00:07:04.190 --> 00:07:08.110
feeling momentarily that I might
be being punked in some way,

00:07:08.110 --> 00:07:10.940
in some sort of Candid
Camera stunt or something,

00:07:10.940 --> 00:07:13.430
that someone had
put him up to this.

00:07:13.430 --> 00:07:16.210
But again, I really
had no reason

00:07:16.210 --> 00:07:19.580
to think-- in fact it seemed
a little crazy for me to think

00:07:19.580 --> 00:07:22.200
that this seemingly
guileless person was

00:07:22.200 --> 00:07:24.110
in on some sort
of elaborate prank

00:07:24.110 --> 00:07:26.120
that was taking
weeks to develop.

00:07:26.120 --> 00:07:28.050
And who'd want to do
this to me anyway?

00:07:28.050 --> 00:07:31.250
I barely knew any of the other
waiters or staff at this place.

00:07:31.250 --> 00:07:34.660
But still, no R-less writer?

00:07:34.660 --> 00:07:36.820
No Melville, no
Poe, no Hemingway,

00:07:36.820 --> 00:07:40.780
just 'Conwad' and
'Gweene.' I mean, come on.

00:07:40.780 --> 00:07:43.600
What are the odds here?

00:07:43.600 --> 00:07:46.080
I was just about to
head back to the kitchen

00:07:46.080 --> 00:07:48.880
to pick up one of my
other table's orders

00:07:48.880 --> 00:07:54.650
when the guy said,
I also love music.

00:07:54.650 --> 00:07:57.220
I took a deep breath.

00:07:57.220 --> 00:07:58.800
'Oh,' I said.

00:07:58.800 --> 00:08:00.100
'What kinds of music?'

00:08:00.100 --> 00:08:01.900
And again he thought
for a moment or two.

00:08:01.900 --> 00:08:07.300
And then he said, I love
the "Wamones," "Woxy"

00:08:07.300 --> 00:08:13.200
Music.' And especially, and
this he said in a much louder,

00:08:13.200 --> 00:08:19.200
more declarative voice,
'especially Guns N' "Woses."'

00:08:19.200 --> 00:08:22.180
And at this moment,
I was positive I

00:08:22.180 --> 00:08:24.090
heard people sniggering,
that there were

00:08:24.090 --> 00:08:26.830
little contingents
of my cohorts huddled

00:08:26.830 --> 00:08:29.140
in corners of the
dining room barely able

00:08:29.140 --> 00:08:30.630
to control their laughter.

00:08:30.630 --> 00:08:33.630
And I felt this
radiant heat rising

00:08:33.630 --> 00:08:34.789
from the back of my neck.

00:08:34.789 --> 00:08:39.340
And I felt as if my face must
have been bright, bright red

00:08:39.340 --> 00:08:40.380
with humiliation.

00:08:40.380 --> 00:08:45.240
And although I never actually
saw anyone laughing at me,

00:08:45.240 --> 00:08:46.600
I knew that they were.

00:08:46.600 --> 00:08:51.360
Who they were and why they did
that to me, I'll never know.

00:08:51.360 --> 00:08:57.520
And yes, it's possible that
a middle aged man from Jersey

00:08:57.520 --> 00:09:00.370
City with R-labialization
could like

00:09:00.370 --> 00:09:03.970
'Wob Woys,' 'pwime wib,'
'Gwaham Gweene,' and Guns

00:09:03.970 --> 00:09:09.000
N' 'Woses.' But it's such a
remote possibility it has to be

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:10.350
pretty much inconceivable.

00:09:10.350 --> 00:09:15.930
Someone or some people
were behind all of this.

00:09:15.930 --> 00:09:19.940
And their identities
will also remain forever

00:09:19.940 --> 00:09:22.250
in the nine enigma file.

00:09:22.250 --> 00:09:25.520
And I also like to think that
this particular event, I guess

00:09:25.520 --> 00:09:27.990
because I felt so
abjectly alone,

00:09:27.990 --> 00:09:31.200
so on display at that
moment in that dining

00:09:31.200 --> 00:09:34.860
room full of people,
in that particular food

00:09:34.860 --> 00:09:38.020
court, that this event
not only instilled

00:09:38.020 --> 00:09:40.590
in me a wariness
and a hypervigilance

00:09:40.590 --> 00:09:44.440
and suspiciousness and maybe
even paranoia that have never

00:09:44.440 --> 00:09:49.920
abated, but also a weird
masochistic love of precisely

00:09:49.920 --> 00:09:52.230
this sort of public humiliation.

00:09:52.230 --> 00:09:55.700
And I'm not saying
that's necessarily

00:09:55.700 --> 00:09:58.170
a good thing or a bad thing.

00:09:58.170 --> 00:10:00.520
I'm just saying that
that's probably why

00:10:00.520 --> 00:10:03.270
we're all here this morning.

00:10:03.270 --> 00:10:10.717
And again, I'm extremely
grateful for the opportunity."

00:10:10.717 --> 00:10:11.550
