about it, and he freaked.

00:30:22.090 --> 00:30:23.480
He hated the idea.

00:30:23.480 --> 00:30:25.900
And I immediately regretted
having told him about it.

00:30:25.900 --> 00:30:27.720
It was a huge mistake.

00:30:27.720 --> 00:30:32.330
And sometimes I think that
that's actually why he left.

00:30:32.330 --> 00:30:34.790
He just want it to be
completely off the radar,

00:30:34.790 --> 00:30:36.970
left alone, completely
inconspicuous,

00:30:36.970 --> 00:30:39.270
completely off camera.

00:30:39.270 --> 00:30:42.310
I don't know if he'd been
abused in his life or what,

00:30:42.310 --> 00:30:44.570
but he just wanted to
be able to relax and act

00:30:44.570 --> 00:30:47.130
as loony and as
dorky as he wanted to

00:30:47.130 --> 00:30:49.860
without having to worry about
what anyone else thought.

00:30:49.860 --> 00:30:51.820
And I think the idea
of a documentary

00:30:51.820 --> 00:30:53.140
just really shook him up.

00:30:53.140 --> 00:30:56.610
It really spooked him.

00:30:56.610 --> 00:30:59.440
And I think I mentioned
before that I've

00:30:59.440 --> 00:31:04.310
tried to reconjure his face
from the configuration of cracks

00:31:04.310 --> 00:31:07.830
in the tile floor
of other bathrooms.

00:31:07.830 --> 00:31:09.390
In fact I was
sitting on the toilet

00:31:09.390 --> 00:31:12.030
in the mens' room in the
Nordstrom at this mall

00:31:12.030 --> 00:31:14.550
actually, and I
thought I discerned

00:31:14.550 --> 00:31:17.230
his face in some
craquelure on the floor.

00:31:17.230 --> 00:31:21.400
And I remember I was
concentrating so hard on it,

00:31:21.400 --> 00:31:25.890
trying so hard to force a
jumble of disparate features

00:31:25.890 --> 00:31:30.980
into a recognizable physiognomy
that I was actually straining,

00:31:30.980 --> 00:31:34.690
you know, pressing in that way
that can cause hemorrhoids.

00:31:34.690 --> 00:31:37.900
So I had to stop.

00:31:37.900 --> 00:31:43.880
I've had that sudden frisson,
that jolt of, it's him,

00:31:43.880 --> 00:31:45.140
many times.

00:31:45.140 --> 00:31:48.760
And I'll squint and I'll
look from different angles,

00:31:48.760 --> 00:31:52.170
and it's inevitably
a false alarm.

00:31:52.170 --> 00:31:54.710
It's not him.

00:31:54.710 --> 00:32:00.570
And it's a big, big
letdown, it really is.

00:32:00.570 --> 00:32:04.890
It's a shitty feeling
But that's what

00:32:04.890 --> 00:32:10.130
nonfiction is people, shitty
feelings and encounters

00:32:10.130 --> 00:32:11.750
with death.

00:32:11.750 --> 00:32:18.100
And that's why we're
here this morning."

00:32:18.100 --> 00:32:18.623
Thank you.

00:32:18.623 --> 00:32:19.896
[APPLAUSE]

00:32:19.896 --> 00:32:24.710
Now I want to read you
one last little thing,

00:32:24.710 --> 00:32:31.490
and then we'll see.

00:32:31.490 --> 00:32:33.690
"I don't know if
you guys have ever

00:32:33.690 --> 00:32:37.170
run into people who do
this cute sort of thing

00:32:37.170 --> 00:32:41.630
when you're talking to
them, where if you say XYZ,

00:32:41.630 --> 00:32:44.500
they'll say you're XYZ.

00:32:44.500 --> 00:32:47.110
I knew this girl who used
to do it all the time.

00:32:47.110 --> 00:32:50.300
Like I'd say something
like, 'There's a hegemonic

00:32:50.300 --> 00:32:53.730
comparative in cross-training
sneakers.' And she'd say,

00:32:53.730 --> 00:32:58.980
'You're a hegemonic imperative
in cross-training sneakers.' Or

00:32:58.980 --> 00:33:01.730
we'd be out at a
restaurant, and I'd say,

00:33:01.730 --> 00:33:06.420
'That pasta looks like a bowl
of infant foreskins.' And

00:33:06.420 --> 00:33:12.130
she'd say, 'You're a bowl
of infant foreskins.'

00:33:12.130 --> 00:33:15.520
So once the Imaginary
Intern said to me--

00:33:15.520 --> 00:33:18.210
and I don't remember
what the context was--

00:33:18.210 --> 00:33:23.270
but he said that memory, and
in a sense autobiography,

00:33:23.270 --> 00:33:27.520
is like a rash that
blossoms and fades.

00:33:27.520 --> 00:33:30.530
And I said to him, 'You're
like a rash that blossoms

00:33:30.530 --> 00:33:38.560
and fades.' And then,
after he was gone,

00:33:38.560 --> 00:33:44.070
I realized that he actually was
like a rash that had blossomed

00:33:44.070 --> 00:33:53.192
and faded, an ache that
time will never assuage."

00:33:53.192 --> 00:33:56.440
[APPLAUSE]

00:33:56.440 --> 00:33:58.900
Thank you.

00:33:58.900 --> 00:34:05.450
You're the greatest
audience I've ever had,

00:34:05.450 --> 00:34:07.154
as I expected you to be.

00:34:11.600 --> 00:34:15.850
I don't know what more to say.

00:34:15.850 --> 00:34:19.880
Do you have any questions
about anything at all?

00:34:23.817 --> 00:34:26.440
AUDIENCE: Why did you decide
to write an autobiography?

00:34:26.440 --> 00:34:28.000
MARK LEYNER: Oh,
I think you have

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:29.208
to come up to the microphone.

00:34:33.830 --> 00:34:35.682
Take your time.

00:34:35.682 --> 00:34:36.598
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:34:42.502 --> 00:34:45.060
Hello.

00:34:45.060 --> 00:34:47.948
Why did you decide to write an
autobiography at this point?

00:34:55.284 --> 00:34:56.284
MARK LEYNER: Here's why.

00:35:03.220 --> 00:35:06.320
When I'm writing a
book, I look at my work

00:35:06.320 --> 00:35:12.710
in a way that may be different
from the majority of writers.

00:35:12.710 --> 00:35:15.200
I get the sense that it is.

00:35:15.200 --> 00:35:18.190
I'm not the sort
of writer or person

00:35:18.190 --> 00:35:22.340
who thinks there are
things I need to get out,

00:35:22.340 --> 00:35:25.680
there things that I
need to convey to people

00:35:25.680 --> 00:35:29.540
or there's some sort of an inner
narrative that I'm storing up

00:35:29.540 --> 00:35:33.200
and I need to convey
in some way or that I

00:35:33.200 --> 00:35:37.530
have certain incredible
theories or sentiments that I

00:35:37.530 --> 00:35:39.380
need to convey.

00:35:39.380 --> 00:35:46.270
Books to me are always-- I think
I was very influenced by when

00:35:46.270 --> 00:35:50.060
I was a teenager, or let's
say 14, 15, 16, by the way

00:35:50.060 --> 00:35:51.750
painters thought
about their work

00:35:51.750 --> 00:35:55.390
and painters would think about
doing a series of paintings

00:35:55.390 --> 00:35:57.240
with certain kind of
technical problems

00:35:57.240 --> 00:35:59.604
or certain aesthetic
technical problems

00:35:59.604 --> 00:36:00.770
that they were dealing with.

00:36:00.770 --> 00:36:04.810
And then another series
would be somehow maybe a kind

00:36:04.810 --> 00:36:07.920
of dialectic with the last
series or something very

00:36:07.920 --> 00:36:11.156
different or a kind of perhaps
advancement on the ideas

00:36:11.156 --> 00:36:12.030
of that or something.

00:36:12.030 --> 00:36:14.960
And that's sort of how I
think about these things.

00:36:14.960 --> 00:36:18.250
So for the longest time,
most of my life as a writer,

00:36:18.250 --> 00:36:21.220
I had very much avoided
what you would call anything

00:36:21.220 --> 00:36:24.300
autobiographical,
because I just thought

00:36:24.300 --> 00:36:29.720
that was the least interesting
part of what I know or think

00:36:29.720 --> 00:36:31.910
about.

00:36:31.910 --> 00:36:36.280
So I somewhat arbitrarily
just embargoed all of that.

00:36:36.280 --> 00:36:39.490
And then I had stopped
writing a little bit

00:36:39.490 --> 00:36:43.960
and was doing movie
and TV kind of writing.

00:36:43.960 --> 00:36:46.310
And then when I came
back to writing books,

00:36:46.310 --> 00:36:52.630
I wrote a book called The
Sugar Frosted Nutsack."

00:36:52.630 --> 00:36:59.720
And it had nothing of me in it.

00:36:59.720 --> 00:37:02.710
My other books had had a kind
of very fictionalized version

00:37:02.710 --> 00:37:08.712
of me, a very, very hyperbolic,
artificial version of the I,

00:37:08.712 --> 00:37:12.180
the first person subject.

00:37:12.180 --> 00:37:16.180
Then that book
had nothing of me.

00:37:16.180 --> 00:37:18.730
It was about a set
of gods and goddesses

00:37:18.730 --> 00:37:20.960
and a person named
Ike who believed--

00:37:20.960 --> 00:37:22.920
like was the only person
on Earth who believed

00:37:22.920 --> 00:37:25.720
in these gods and goddesses.

00:37:25.720 --> 00:37:28.030
Which as I point out doesn't
mean they didn't exist,

00:37:28.030 --> 00:37:31.520
it just meant they
chose to only be

00:37:31.520 --> 00:37:33.060
in the head of this one person.

00:37:33.060 --> 00:37:36.210
I think that's
perfectly plausible,

00:37:36.210 --> 00:37:38.640
that gods and goddesses would
be-- could behave that way,

00:37:38.640 --> 00:37:41.680
probably would behave that way.

00:37:41.680 --> 00:37:45.670
So this book I decided,
let me try to do something

00:37:45.670 --> 00:37:50.140
where I'm in every--
something auto--

00:37:50.140 --> 00:37:55.770
like see what was that fear
or objection to talking

00:37:55.770 --> 00:37:59.270
about, you know, musing.

00:37:59.270 --> 00:38:01.860
I really think we all have a
kind of finite set of stories

00:38:01.860 --> 00:38:05.777
that retrospectively determine
who we think we are and how we

00:38:05.777 --> 00:38:07.860
present ourselves to other
people or to ourselves,

00:38:07.860 --> 00:38:10.130
you know, maybe 20 stories.

00:38:10.130 --> 00:38:12.240
And you find yourself
drinking is good for this.

00:38:12.240 --> 00:38:16.280
You find yourself telling all
of them, in any given night.

00:38:16.280 --> 00:38:20.070
After a number of hours,
you will dip into those

00:38:20.070 --> 00:38:23.140
and exhaust them by 2:00,
3:00 in the morning,

00:38:23.140 --> 00:38:24.240
and just start again.

00:38:26.940 --> 00:38:31.990
So I said, let's think
about that and use those.

00:38:31.990 --> 00:38:37.400
And we discovered, it's just as
interesting and uninteresting

00:38:37.400 --> 00:38:41.050
as all the sort of
miscellaneous detritus

00:38:41.050 --> 00:38:43.720
that you use in
your writing anyway.

00:38:43.720 --> 00:38:44.702
It's the same.

00:38:44.702 --> 00:38:46.160
You know, the sort
of membrane that

00:38:46.160 --> 00:38:48.900
separates what you think of as
yourself and the outside world

00:38:48.900 --> 00:38:53.370
is very porous and it's the
same stuff floating in and out.

00:38:53.370 --> 00:38:56.700
So why I spent my whole life
avoiding it, I don't know now.

00:38:56.700 --> 00:38:59.406
But now that's out
of my system, so--

00:39:03.629 --> 00:39:05.795
AUDIENCE: So I think you
just answered my questions,

00:39:05.795 --> 00:39:07.000
so I'll ask a different one.

00:39:07.000 --> 00:39:10.630
When you wrote the previous one,
"The Sugar Frosted Nutsack,"

00:39:10.630 --> 00:39:13.740
when you started that book,
how much of its structure

00:39:13.740 --> 00:39:16.370
did you already have in mind?

00:39:16.370 --> 00:39:17.942
Did you already
have it or did it

00:39:17.942 --> 00:39:19.150
merge as you started writing?

00:39:22.980 --> 00:39:24.420
MARK LEYNER: That
book, which I'm

00:39:24.420 --> 00:39:28.670
assuming, out of my
saintly humility,

00:39:28.670 --> 00:39:33.460
that you haven't
read, again, I have

00:39:33.460 --> 00:39:37.840
very-- I don't know what you
call them-- architectonic

00:39:37.840 --> 00:39:40.900
or geometric senses of books.

00:39:40.900 --> 00:39:44.600
I really have an idea of
what the shape of a book is.

00:39:44.600 --> 00:39:46.590
And it's much more
important to me

00:39:46.590 --> 00:39:51.460
than the story or
the characters.

00:39:51.460 --> 00:39:55.804
The shape of that book
was a kind of vortex.

00:39:55.804 --> 00:39:57.470
And in fact at the
end, there's an image

00:39:57.470 --> 00:40:02.120
at the end of the entire
book being embroidered around

00:40:02.120 --> 00:40:04.060
and around and around
and around like a vortex

00:40:04.060 --> 00:40:10.220
in a baseball cap, until you get
to that little nub on the top

00:40:10.220 --> 00:40:13.680
and the book's sort
of ending there.

00:40:13.680 --> 00:40:17.570
And that's how I always
imagined that book, some sort

00:40:17.570 --> 00:40:20.520
of spinning and spinning
and then getting

00:40:20.520 --> 00:40:24.560
in tighter and tighter and
tighter whirls of the vortex.

00:40:24.560 --> 00:40:29.690
This book, "Gone with the Mind,"
I had, from the beginning,

00:40:29.690 --> 00:40:33.810
an idea of doing a book
in the form of a reading,

00:40:33.810 --> 00:40:35.970
in kind of three
acts, that there'd

00:40:35.970 --> 00:40:42.960
be an introduction,
the reading, and a Q&amp;A.

00:40:42.960 --> 00:40:51.290
I found almost no advice you
get as a writer is useful.

00:40:51.290 --> 00:40:53.320
And almost everything
I've ever been told

00:40:53.320 --> 00:40:57.840
I've been most successful
by doing the opposite.

00:40:57.840 --> 00:40:59.280
And I still try to do that.

00:40:59.280 --> 00:41:04.520
If I show something to someone
and they say, oh it's very,

00:41:04.520 --> 00:41:09.500
I don't know, it's
pornographic, I'd

00:41:09.500 --> 00:41:11.360
just try to make it
more pornographic.

00:41:11.360 --> 00:41:14.770
Or it's self-indulgent, I
make it more self-indulgent.

00:41:14.770 --> 00:41:16.142
Just do the opposite.

00:41:16.142 --> 00:41:17.930
Or it's too
sentimental, I make it

00:41:17.930 --> 00:41:23.500
sickening like drenched
in molasses sentiment.

00:41:23.500 --> 00:41:25.850
They're just showing me
the direction to go to.

00:41:31.280 --> 00:41:34.210
So what was I going to say?

00:41:37.610 --> 00:41:38.865
I lost my train of thought.

00:41:38.865 --> 00:41:41.580
What were we talking
about, because there

00:41:41.580 --> 00:41:46.290
was a kind of advice
someone gave me about this,

00:41:46.290 --> 00:41:48.740
and now I can't
remember what it was

00:41:48.740 --> 00:41:52.250
and what I did opposite to it.

00:41:52.250 --> 00:41:54.080
Let me think for a second.

00:41:54.080 --> 00:41:56.491
We're talking about this book.

00:41:56.491 --> 00:42:00.964
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] talking
without interrupting yourself,

00:42:00.964 --> 00:42:03.805
and [INAUDIBLE]?

00:42:03.805 --> 00:42:04.680
MARK LEYNER: Exactly.

00:42:04.680 --> 00:42:06.980
Well, it'll come to me or not.

00:42:06.980 --> 00:42:10.260
Anyway, I wish I could remember.

00:42:10.260 --> 00:42:12.090
It was so brilliant.

00:42:17.330 --> 00:42:21.130
Let me just think for
a second about this.

00:42:25.002 --> 00:42:27.570
I don't know, lost it.

00:42:27.570 --> 00:42:35.320
OK, I'm a reliable lecturer
here, half demented.

00:42:35.320 --> 00:42:38.681
Can't even think of what the
beginning of his own sentence

00:42:38.681 --> 00:42:39.180
was.

00:42:39.180 --> 00:42:42.910
Anyway, thank you so
much for coming today

00:42:42.910 --> 00:42:46.400
in the midst of such an
infernal day out there.

00:42:46.400 --> 00:42:50.800
It was great, great to
meet you in this forum.

00:42:50.800 --> 00:42:53.850
[APPLAUSE]

